s were intended to support and how these related to the race politics of the time, the meanings that may have been found in the photographs, and the possible reasons why they were "lost" for a century or more. Each image is accompanied by a brief fictional vignette about the subject's life as imagined by Rogers; these portraits bring the seven subjects to life, adding a fascinating human dimension to the historical material.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aPhotographyxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPhotographyxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aRacism in anthropologyzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aRacismzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlaveszSouth CarolinazColumbia RegionvBiography. 0aSlaveszSouth CarolinazColumbia RegionvPictorial works. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh1 aBlight, David W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300163285423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300163285.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles